{"title_page": "Leslie Cockburn", "text_new": "{{short description|American investigative journalist and filmmaker}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Leslie Cockburn \n|birth_name  = Leslie Corkill Redlich\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1952|9|2}}\n|birth_place = [[San Mateo, California]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = {{marriage|[[Andrew Cockburn]]|1977}}\n|children    = 3, including [[Olivia Wilde]]\n|education   = [[Yale University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[SOAS, University of London|University of London]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n}}\n'''Leslie Cockburn''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|o\u028a|b|\u0259r|n}} {{respell|KOH|b\u0259rn}} born '''Leslie Corkill Redlich'''; September 2, 1952) is an [[United States|American]] [[Investigative journalism|investigative journalist]], and [[filmmaker]]. Her investigative television segments have aired on [[CBS]], [[NBC]], ''[[PBS Frontline]]'', and ''[[60 Minutes]]''. She has won an [[Emmy Award]], [[The Hillman Prize]], [[Alfred I. duPont\u2013Columbia University Award]], [[Robert F. Kennedy Journalism Award]], and the [[George Polk Award]].\n\nShe was the  2018 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[Virginia]]'s [[Virginia's 5th congressional district|5th district]] in the [[U.S. House of Representatives]], losing to Republican [[Denver Riggleman]].\n\n==Early life==\nLeslie Cockburn (n\u00e9e Leslie Corkill Redlich) was born in [[San Mateo, California]] and raised in [[Hillsborough, California]]. She is the daughter of Jeanne (Fulcher) and Christopher Rudolph Redlich, a shipping magnate.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Christopher-Redlich-2690057.php |title=Obituary: Christopher Redlich |date=December 20, 2000 |newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/REDLICH-Jeanne-Fulcher-2877728.php |title=Obituary: Redlich, Jeanne Fulcher |date=February 5, 2002 |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> She grew up in a family of hunters and supports gun control.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=http://wmra.org/post/rep-tom-garretts-challengers-5th-district#stream/0 |title=Rep. Tom Garrett's Challengers in the 5th District |last=Gallorini|first=Marguerite |work=[[WMRA]] |access-date=June 6, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nLeslie attended the [[Santa Catalina School]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.santacatalina.org/upper-school/our-program/arts/alumnae-in-the-arts |title=Alumnae in the Arts: Leslie Cockburn '70\" |work=Santa Catalina School}}</ref> She then studied at [[Yale University]], entering in the second class of women allowed at the university.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-politics/learning-to-do-a-double-flip-from-red-to-blue-and-from-reporter-to-politician/2018/09/23/3cfa5a6c-99b5-11e8-8d5e-c6c594024954_story.html |title=Learning to do a double flip: From red to blue and from reporter to politician |first=Marc |last=Fisher |date=September 24, 2018 |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=2018-11-07}}</ref> She went on to earn a master's degree from the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]] at the [[University of London]].\n\n==Career==\nCockburn is a former investigative journalist for [[NBC]], [[CBS]], and [[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|PBS ''Frontline'']].<ref name=\":0\" /> While living in [[London]], she started working for [[NBC News]]. Among her early reports was an interview with Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/leslie-cockburn-is-the-only-candidate-whos-dined-with-mick-jagger-and-saddams-sons |title=Leslie Cockburn Is the Only Candidate Who\u2019s Dined With Mick Jagger and Saddam\u2019s Sons |last=Grove |first=Lloyd |date=July 22, 2017 |work=[[The Daily Beast]]}}</ref> In 1978, Cockburn moved to [[CBS]]. During her career, she covered six wars including the U.S.-directed [[Contras|Contra]] War against Nicaragua.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Documentary films===\nIn 1987, Cockburn began producing and reporting documentaries for [[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|PBS ''Frontline'']] in collaboration with her husband, [[Andrew Cockburn]]. They created ''Guns, Drugs, and the CIA'' (1987), a documentary which claimed the CIA assisted and encouraged drug trafficking.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/drugs/archive/gunsdrugscia.html |title=Guns, Drugs, and the CIA (full transcript) |date=May 17, 1988 |work=PBS Frontline}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/05/17/arts/review-television-program-links-cia-to-drug-trafic.html |title=Review/Television; Program Links C.I.A. to Drug Traffic |last=Corry |first=John |date=May 17, 1988 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=June 6, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In 1990, Cockburn produced and co-wrote \"From the Killing Fields\" with [[Peter Jennings]] and [[Tom Yellin]] for the ABC News documentary show ''[[Peter Jennings Reporting]]''. The film alleged that the U.S. had covertly supported the [[Khmer Rouge]] in its return to power in [[Cambodia]] during a genocidal movement responsible for the deaths of millions in the 1970s.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/04/26/arts/review-television-jennings-says-us-helps-khmer-rouge.html |title=Review/Television; Jennings Says U.S. Helps Khmer Rouge |last=Goodman |first=Walter |date=April 26, 1990 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=June 6, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, she and her husband produced the PBS ''Frontline'' documentary ''The War We Left Behind'', which showed the effects of the [[Gulf War]] on Kurdish and Iraqi civilians.<ref>{{Citation |last=Cockburn |first=Leslie |title=Frontline |date=1991 |first2=Andrew |last2=Cockburn |last3=LC Off-Air Taping Collection (Library of Congress) |last4=Copyright Collection (Library of Congress) |publisher=WETA-TV |language=English |oclc=32544497}}</ref> In 1997, Cockburn conceived and co-produced ''[[The Peacemaker (1997 film)|The Peacemaker]]'', starring [[George Clooney]] and [[Nicole Kidman]], a thriller positing a terrorist attack on [[New York City]] with a stolen nuclear weapon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gulftoday.ae/portal/91bf9647-0061-4958-bbc8-2e8fa55f5358.aspx |title=Leslie Cockburn's brave crusade |first=Michael |last=Jansen |date=June 4, 2018 |website=[[Gulf Today]] |access-date=June 6, 2018}}</ref> In 1998, Cockburn served as Ferris Professor of Journalism at [[Princeton University]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.princeton.edu/pr/news/98/c/0512-clips.htm |title=Between The Bookends |first=Ann Lloyd  |last=Merriman |date=May 3, 1998 |newspaper=The Richmond Times Dispatch |via=Princeton in the News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/princetonantholo00prin |url-access=registration |quote=Leslie Cockburn Ferris Professor of Journalism Princeton University |title=The Princeton Anthology of Writing: Favorite Pieces by the Ferris/McGraw Writers at Princeton University |last=McPhee|first=John |date=August 5, 2001 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=9780691086811|language=en}}</ref> In 2000, she produced \"America's Worst Nightmare,\" a [[60 Minutes]] report on political instability in nuclear-armed Pakistan and fundamentalist groups linked to the [[Taliban]], a piece that was recognized as \"strikingly prophetic\" in receiving the [[Alfred I. duPont-Columbia University Award]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0DE2DC153EF93AA25751C1A9679C8B63 |title=Broadcasts On Terrorists Win Awards |first=Bill |last=Carter |date=December 19, 2001 |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=December 28, 2007}}</ref><ref{{cite news |url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/news/01/12/dupont_awards.html |title=2002 duPont-Columbia Awards Recognize Reports on Political Turmoil Among Winners |date=January 12, 2002 |newspaper=Columbia News |access-date=December 24, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===''Dangerous Liaison - The Inside Story of the U.S.-Israeli Covert Relationship''===\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?20968-1/dangerous-liaisons ''Booknotes'' interview with Leslie and Andrew Cockburn, September 1, 1991], [[C-SPAN]]}} \nIn 1991, Cockburn and her husband, Andrew, published their first book together on the military and intelligence relationship between the U.S. and Israel after 1948. This book detailed how, over several decades, Israel had served U.S. interests both through espionage operations in the former Soviet Union, as well as covert operations in Central America and other third world regions where the U.S. was loath to intervene directly.\u00a0The book also detailed Israeli nuclear activities, including U.S, assistance to its bomb-making program and Israeli cooperation with the South African apartheid regime's nuclear weapons program. The book was a national bestseller in the U.S. and Canada. ''Kirkus Reviews'' said the book was \"no thrown-together post-Gulf product, but an unflinching, fact-packed, closely reasoned exploration of our relations with our strongest ally in the Middle East.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/andrew-cockburn/dangerous-liaison/ |title=Dangerous Liaison by Andrew Cockburn & Leslie Cockburn |work=Kirkus Reviews |date=June 1, 1991 |language=en}}</ref>  ''The Chicago Tribune'' said the book \"should stand for a long time as the alpha and omega of the relationship between the United States and Israel...the Cockburns present the history in rich detail.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1991-02-01|title=The secret agent: a simple tale|journal=Choice Reviews Online|volume=28|issue=6|pages=28\u20133158\u201328\u20133158|doi=10.5860/choice.28-3158|issn=0009-4978}}</ref> Other reviewers in the U.S. attacked the book on grounds that it was critical of Israel, often making their case with selective misquotation of what the book actually said.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Codevilla |first=Angelo |date=1992 |title=A Second Italian Republic? |journal=Foreign Affairs |volume=71 |issue=3 |pages=146\u2013164 |doi=10.2307/20045235|issn=0015-7120 |jstor=20045235}}</ref> In Israel itself, the response was more measured.\u00a0''Haaretz'' reviewed it favorably at length, calling it \"credible\" <ref>{{Cite journal |last=Malkin |first=Irad |date=2016-03-07 |title=Libations |journal=Oxford Classical Dictionary |doi=10.1093/acrefore/9780199381135.013.3676}}</ref> Maariv acquired the serial rights.\n\n===''American Casino''===\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?290533-1/qa-leslie-andrew-cockburn ''Q&A'' interview with Leslie and Andrew Cockburn on ''American Casino'', January 3, 2010], [[C-SPAN]]}} \nIn 2009, Cockburn directed and co-produced (with husband Andrew Cockburn) her first [[feature film|feature]] documentary for theatrical release, ''[[American Casino (documentary film)|American Casino]].'' It follows the [[subprime mortgage crisis]] in the United States which led to the greatest financial crisis since the [[Great Depression]]. Cockburn and her husband began filming in January 2008, and documented the financial machinations and miscalculations on Wall Street that produced the disaster, and also documented its effects on several Baltimore homeowners struggling to stay afloat. The film premiered at New York's [[Tribeca Film Festival]] in April 2009.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/05/01/AR2009050101722.html |title=Washington Couple Behind 'American Casino,' a Documentary of U.S. Financial Woes |date=May 3, 2009 |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=June 6, 2018 |language=en-US |issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described it as a \"searing expose of the subprime mortgage crisis (matching) Wall Street's numbers and graphics to the flesh-and-blood individuals whose lives have been devastated by the deliberate machinations of bankers and traders.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117940114.html?categoryid=31&cs=1 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430143923/http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117940114.html?categoryid=31&cs=1 |archivedate=2009-04-30 |title=American Casino Review - Read Variety's Analysis Of The Movie American Casino |date=April 30, 2009 |work=Variety |access-date=June 6, 2018}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' said it was \"a terrific documentary chronicling the subprime-mortgage mess and the financial collapse.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2009/09/07/out-of-the-shadows |title=Out of the Shadows |work=The New Yorker |access-date=June 6, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' said it was \"a meticulously structured film.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/02/movies/02american.html |title=Homeowners Left in the Lurch: a Documentary by Leslie and Andrew Cockburn |last=Holden |first=Stephen |date=September 1, 2009 |work=The New York Times |access-date=June 6, 2018 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\nCockburn has won [[The Hillman Prize]] (1984),<ref>{{cite web |title=The Hillman Prize Previous Honorees |url=http://www.hillmanfoundation.org/hillman-prizes/us/honorees?page=8 |work=Sidney Hillman Foundation |accessdate=June 7, 2018}}</ref> the [[George Polk Award]] (2010),<ref>{{cite web |title=Another Polk Award For \"60 Minutes\" |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/another-polk-award-for-60-minutes/ |work=CBS News |accessdate=June 7, 2018}}</ref> and the 1991 [[Robert F. Kennedy Journalism Award]], along with Peter Jennings and Tom Yellin.<ref>{{cite news |title=Winners Announced for Kennedy Awards |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/04/16/us/winners-announced-for-kennedy-awards.html |accessdate=June 7, 2018 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=April 16, 1991}}</ref> Cockburn's work has received multiple [[Emmy]] nominations, and her 1998 documentary ''Yuri The Great'' won an Emmy Award in 1999.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/pbs-cbs-garner-news-emmys/ |title=PBS, CBS Garner News Emmys |work=CBS News |access-date=June 6, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://emmyonline.com/download/20th-Annual-News-Documentary-Emmy-Awards-For-Programming-Originally-Aired-in-Calendar-Year-1998-Winner_2.pdf |title=20th Annual News Documentary Emmy Awards For Programming Originally Aired in Calendar Year 1998 -Winners |last= |first= |date= |website=Emmy Online |access-date=June 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0168298/awards|title=Leslie Cockburn|website=IMDb|access-date=June 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n{{Main|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Virginia#District 5}}\nCockburn was the 2018 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[Virginia's 5th congressional district]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]]. Cockburn announced her candidacy in July 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rappnews.com/2017/07/15/rappahannock-resident-leslie-cockburn-launches-bid-for-u-s-congress-seat/|title=Rappahannock resident Leslie Cockburn launches bid for U.S...|first=John|last=McCaslin|date=July 15, 2017|work=RappNews |accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref> and secured a large majority of delegates over several rival candidates for the party's nomination in May 2018 at the district Democratic convention to succeed the outgoing Republican representative [[Tom Garrett (Virginia politician)|Tom Garrett]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roanoke.com/news/politics/cockburn-receives-th-district-democratic-nomination/article_f5e08b44-9431-5303-8224-4dc49dc02910.html |title=Cockburn receives 5th District Democratic nomination |date=May 5, 2018 |last=Hammel |first=Tyler |work=The Daily Progress |via=Roanoke.com}}</ref>\n\nAfter winning her party's nomination, she lost her election bid to her Republican opponent, [[Denver Riggleman]], in the 2018 general election; Riggleman garnered 165,339 votes (53.2%) compared to Cockburn's 145,040 votes (46.7%) and 547 votes (0.2%) were cast as [[write-ins]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://results.elections.virginia.gov/vaelections/2018%20November%20General/Site/Member%20House%20of%20Representatives%20(05).html |title=2018 November General Election |work=Government of Virginia |date=1980-01-01 |accessdate=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCockburn lives in [[Rappahannock County, Virginia]], with her husband, [[Andrew Cockburn]], a journalist and film producer. They married in San Francisco in 1977 and have co-authored several books.<ref name=\"burkes\">{{cite book |editor-last=Mosley |editor-first=Charles |title=Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage |edition=107th |volume=1 |page=120 |location=Wilmington, Delaware |publisher=Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd. |year=2003}}</ref> They have three children together: Chloe Francis Cockburn (April 3, 1979), [[Olivia Wilde]] (March 10, 1984), and Charles Philip Cockburn (January 31, 1993).<ref name=\"burkes\" />\n\nCockburn had two brothers-in-law, the late [[Alexander Cockburn]] and [[Patrick Cockburn]], and the mystery writer [[Sarah Caudwell]] was her half-sister in law. Her former son-in-law was [[Tao Ruspoli]] and her current son-in-law is [[Jason Sudeikis]], and journalists [[Laura Flanders]] and [[Stephanie Flanders]] are her half-nieces by marriage, daughters of her half-brother in law [[Michael Flanders]]. Her parents-in-law were [[Claud Cockburn|Claud]] and Patricia Cockburn. She has four grandchildren.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Cockburn, Leslie (1998). ''Looking for Trouble: One Woman, Six Wars and a Revolution'',<ref name=\"Democracy Now!\">{{cite web | url=http://www.democracynow.org/1998/4/27/interview_with_leslie_cockburn | title=Interview with Leslie Cockburn | work=[[Democracy Now!]] | date=April 27, 1998 | accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref> [[Anchor Books]], {{ISBN|0-385-48355-4}}\n*Cockburn, Leslie (with Andrew Cockburn) (1997). ''One Point Safe, the True Story of Russian Nuclear Security'', Doubleday, {{ISBN|0-385-48560-3}}\n*Cockburn, Leslie (with Andrew Cockburn) (1991). ''Dangerous Liaison: The Inside Story of the U.S.-Israeli Covert Relationship'', HarperCollins Publishers, {{ISBN|0-06-016444-1}}\n*Cockburn, Leslie (1987). ''Out of Control: The Story of the Reagan Administration's Secret War in Nicaragua, the Illegal Arms Pipeline, and the Contra Drug Connection''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190204153723/https://www.lesliecockburnforcongress.com/ Leslie Cockburn for Congress] - campaign website\n*{{C-SPAN|Leslie Cockburn}}\n**[http://www.c-span.org/video/?290533-1/qa-leslie-andrew-cockburn C-SPAN ''Q&A'' interview with Andrew and Leslie Cockburn about ''American Casino'', January 3, 2010]\n*{{IMDb name|0168298}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cockburn, Leslie}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of SOAS University of London]]\n[[Category:American documentary filmmakers]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:American foreign policy writers]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American television news producers]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:American women war correspondents]]\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:Cockburn family|Leslie]]\n[[Category:People from Hillsborough, California]]\n[[Category:People from San Mateo, California]]\n[[Category:Princeton University faculty]]\n[[Category:Television producers from California]]\n[[Category:Women memoirists]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Virginia Democrats]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Women television producers]]\n[[Category:Women documentary filmmakers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American investigative journalist and filmmaker}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Leslie Cockburn \n|birth_name  = Leslie Corkill Redlich\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1952|9|2}}\n|birth_place = [[San Mateo, California]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = {{marriage|[[Andrew Cockburn]]|1977}}\n|children    = 3, including [[Olivia Wilde]]\n|education   = [[Yale University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[SOAS, University of London|University of London]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n}}\n'''Leslie Cockburn''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|o\u028a|b|\u0259r|n}} {{respell|KOH|b\u0259rn}} born '''Leslie Corkill Redlich'''; September 2, 1952) is an [[United States|American]] [[Investigative journalism|investigative journalist]], and [[filmmaker]]. Her investigative television segments have aired on [[CBS]], [[NBC]], ''[[PBS Frontline]]'', and ''[[60 Minutes]]''. She has won an [[Emmy Award]], [[The Hillman Prize]], [[Alfred I. duPont\u2013Columbia University Award]], [[Robert F. Kennedy Journalism Award]], and the [[George Polk Award]].\n\nShe was the  2018 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[Virginia]]'s [[Virginia's 5th congressional district|5th district]] in the [[U.S. House of Representatives]], losing to Republican [[Denver Riggleman]].\n\n==Early life==\nLeslie Cockburn (n\u00e9e Leslie Corkill Redlich) was born in [[San Mateo, California]] and raised in [[Hillsborough, California]]. She is the daughter of Jeanne (Fulcher) and Christopher Rudolph Redlich, a shipping magnate.<ref>San Francisco Chronicle obituary December 20, 2000</ref><ref>https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/REDLICH-Jeanne-Fulcher-2877728.php</ref> She grew up in a family of hunters and supports gun control.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://wmra.org/post/rep-tom-garretts-challengers-5th-district#stream/0|title=Rep. Tom Garrett's Challengers in the 5th District|last=Gallorini|first=Marguerite|access-date=June 6, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nLeslie attended the [[Santa Catalina School]].<ref>[https://www.santacatalina.org/upper-school/our-program/arts/alumnae-in-the-arts \"Alumnae in the Arts: Leslie Cockburn '70\"],</ref> She then studied at [[Yale University]], entering in the second class of women allowed at the university.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-politics/learning-to-do-a-double-flip-from-red-to-blue-and-from-reporter-to-politician/2018/09/23/3cfa5a6c-99b5-11e8-8d5e-c6c594024954_story.html |title=Learning to do a double flip: From red to blue and from reporter to politician |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=2018-11-07}}</ref> She went on to earn a master's degree from the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]] at the [[University of London]].\n\n==Career==\nCockburn is a former investigative journalist for [[NBC]], [[CBS]], and [[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|PBS ''Frontline'']].<ref name=\":0\" /> While living in [[London]], she started working for [[NBC News]]. Among her early reports was an interview with Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]].<ref>Grove, Lloyd. [https://www.thedailybeast.com/leslie-cockburn-is-the-only-candidate-whos-dined-with-mick-jagger-and-saddams-sons \"Leslie Cockburn Is the Only Candidate Who\u2019s Dined With Mick Jagger and Saddam\u2019s Sons\"], ''[[The Daily Beast]]'', July 22, 2017.</ref> In 1978, Cockburn moved to [[CBS]]. During her career, she covered six wars including the U.S.-directed [[Contras|Contra]] War against Nicaragua.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Documentary films===\nIn 1987, Cockburn began producing and reporting documentaries for [[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|PBS ''Frontline'']] in collaboration with her husband, [[Andrew Cockburn]]. They created ''Guns, Drugs, and the CIA'' (1987), a documentary which claimed the CIA assisted and encouraged drug trafficking.<ref>''[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/drugs/archive/gunsdrugscia.html Guns, Drugs, and the CIA full transcript]'' PBS Frontline page</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/05/17/arts/review-television-program-links-cia-to-drug-trafic.html|title=Review/Television; Program Links C.I.A. to Drug Trafic|last=Corry|first=John|access-date=June 6, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In 1990, Cockburn produced and co-wrote \"From the Killing Fields\" with [[Peter Jennings]] and [[Tom Yellin]] for the ABC News documentary show ''[[Peter Jennings Reporting]]''. The film alleged that the U.S. had covertly supported the [[Khmer Rouge]] in its return to power in [[Cambodia]] during a genocidal movement responsible for the deaths of millions in the 1970s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/04/26/arts/review-television-jennings-says-us-helps-khmer-rouge.html|title=Review/Television; Jennings Says U.S. Helps Khmer Rouge|last=Goodman|first=Walter|access-date=June 6, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, she and her husband produced the PBS ''Frontline'' documentary ''The War We Left Behind'', which showed the effects of the [[Gulf War]] on Kurdish and Iraqi civilians.<ref>{{Citation|last=Cockburn|first=Leslie|title=Frontline.|date=1991|last2=Cockburn|last3=LC Off-Air Taping Collection (Library of Congress)|last4=Copyright Collection (Library of Congress)|first2=Andrew|publisher=WETA-TV|language=English|oclc=32544497}}</ref> In 1997, Cockburn conceived and co-produced ''[[The Peacemaker (1997 film)|The Peacemaker]]'', starring [[George Clooney]] and [[Nicole Kidman]], a thriller positing a terrorist attack on [[New York City]] with a stolen nuclear weapon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulftoday.ae/portal/91bf9647-0061-4958-bbc8-2e8fa55f5358.aspx|title=gulftoday.ae {{!}} Michael Jansen: Leslie Cockburn's brave crusade|website=gulftoday.ae|access-date=June 6, 2018}}</ref> In 1998, Cockburn served as Ferris Professor of Journalism at [[Princeton University]].<ref>''[https://www.princeton.edu/pr/news/98/c/0512-clips.htm Princeton in the News]'' Article, May 12, 1998</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/princetonantholo00prin|url-access=registration|quote=Leslie Cockburn Ferris Professor of Journalism Princeton University.|title=The Princeton Anthology of Writing: Favorite Pieces by the Ferris/McGraw Writers at Princeton University|last=McPhee|first=John|date=August 5, 2001|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=9780691086811|language=en}}</ref> In 2000, she produced \"America's Worst Nightmare,\" a [[60 Minutes]] report on political instability in nuclear-armed Pakistan and fundamentalist groups linked to the [[Taliban]], a piece that was recognized as \"strikingly prophetic\" in receiving the [[Alfred I. duPont-Columbia University Award]] in 2001.<ref>Carter, Bill. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0DE2DC153EF93AA25751C1A9679C8B63 \"Broadcasts On Terrorists Win Awards\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 19, 2001. Accessed December 28, 2007.</ref><ref>''[http://www.columbia.edu/cu/news/01/12/dupont_awards.html 2002 duPont-Columbia Awards Recognize Reports on Political Turmoil Among Winners]'', Article, Columbia News, January 12, 2002, accessed December 24, 2007</ref>\n\n===''Dangerous Liaison - The Inside Story of the U.S.-Israeli Covert Relationship''===\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?20968-1/dangerous-liaisons ''Booknotes'' interview with Leslie and Andrew Cockburn, September 1, 1991], [[C-SPAN]]}} \nIn 1991, Cockburn and her husband, Andrew, published their first book together on the military and intelligence relationship between the U.S. and Israel after 1948. This book detailed how, over several decades, Israel had served U.S. interests both through espionage operations in the former Soviet Union, as well as covert operations in Central America and other third world regions where the U.S. was loath to intervene directly.\u00a0The book also detailed Israeli nuclear activities, including U.S, assistance to its bomb-making program and Israeli cooperation with the South African apartheid regime's nuclear weapons program. The book was a national bestseller in the U.S. and Canada. ''Kirkus Reviews'' said the book was \"no thrown-together post-Gulf product, but an unflinching, fact-packed, closely reasoned exploration of our relations with our strongest ally in the Middle East.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/andrew-cockburn/dangerous-liaison/|title=DANGEROUS LIAISON by Andrew Cockburn, Leslie Cockburn {{!}} Kirkus Reviews|language=en}}</ref>  ''The Chicago Tribune'' said the book \"should stand for a long time as the alpha and omega of the relationship between the United States and Israel...the Cockburns present the history in rich detail.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1991-02-01|title=The secret agent: a simple tale|journal=Choice Reviews Online|volume=28|issue=6|pages=28\u20133158\u201328\u20133158|doi=10.5860/choice.28-3158|issn=0009-4978}}</ref> Other reviewers in the U.S. attacked the book on grounds that it was critical of Israel, often making their case with selective misquotation of what the book actually said.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Codevilla|first=Angelo|date=1992|title=A Second Italian Republic?|journal=Foreign Affairs|volume=71|issue=3|pages=146\u2013164|doi=10.2307/20045235|issn=0015-7120|jstor=20045235}}</ref> In Israel itself, the response was more measured.\u00a0 Haaretz reviewed it favorably at length, calling it \"credible\" <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Malkin|first=Irad|date=2016-03-07|title=libations|journal=Oxford Classical Dictionary|doi=10.1093/acrefore/9780199381135.013.3676}}</ref> Maariv acquired the serial rights.\n\n===''American Casino''===\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?290533-1/qa-leslie-andrew-cockburn ''Q&A'' interview with Leslie and Andrew Cockburn on ''American Casino'', January 3, 2010], [[C-SPAN]]}} \nIn 2009, Cockburn directed and co-produced (with husband Andrew Cockburn) her first [[feature film|feature]] documentary for theatrical release, ''[[American Casino (documentary film)|American Casino]].'' It follows the [[subprime mortgage crisis]] in the United States which led to the greatest financial crisis since the [[Great Depression]]. Cockburn and her husband began filming in January 2008, and documented the financial machinations and miscalculations on Wall Street that produced the disaster, and also documented its effects on several Baltimore homeowners struggling to stay afloat. The film premiered at New York's [[Tribeca Film Festival]] in April 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/05/01/AR2009050101722.html|title=Washington Couple Behind 'American Casino,' a Documentary of U.S. Financial Woes|date=May 3, 2009|access-date=June 6, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described it as a \"searing expose of the subprime mortgage crisis (matching) Wall Street's numbers and graphics to the flesh-and-blood individuals whose lives have been devastated by the deliberate machinations of bankers and traders.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117940114.html?categoryid=31&cs=1|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430143923/http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117940114.html?categoryid=31&cs=1|archivedate=2009-04-30|title=American Casino Review - Read Variety's Analysis Of The Movie American Casino|date=April 30, 2009|access-date=June 6, 2018}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' said it was \"a terrific documentary chronicling the subprime-mortgage mess and the financial collapse.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2009/09/07/out-of-the-shadows|title=Out of the Shadows|work=The New Yorker|access-date=June 6, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' said it was \"a meticulously structured film.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/02/movies/02american.html|title=Homeowners Left in the Lurch: a Documentary by Leslie and Andrew Cockburn|last=Holden|first=Stephen|date=September 1, 2009|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 6, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\nCockburn has won [[The Hillman Prize]] (1984),<ref>{{cite web |title=The Hillman Prize Previous Honorees |url=http://www.hillmanfoundation.org/hillman-prizes/us/honorees?page=8 |publisher=Sidney Hillman Foundation |accessdate=June 7, 2018}}</ref> the [[George Polk Award]] (2010),<ref>{{cite web |title=Another Polk Award For \"60 Minutes\" |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/another-polk-award-for-60-minutes/ |publisher=CBS News |accessdate=June 7, 2018}}</ref> and the 1991 [[Robert F. Kennedy Journalism Award]], along with Peter Jennings and Tom Yellin.<ref>{{cite news |title=Winners Announced for Kennedy Awards |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/04/16/us/winners-announced-for-kennedy-awards.html |accessdate=June 7, 2018 |newspaper=New York Times |date=April 16, 1991}}</ref> Cockburn's work has received multiple [[Emmy]] nominations, and her 1998 documentary ''Yuri The Great'' won an Emmy Award in 1999.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/pbs-cbs-garner-news-emmys/|title=PBS, CBS Garner News Emmys|access-date=June 6, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://emmyonline.com/download/20th-Annual-News-Documentary-Emmy-Awards-For-Programming-Originally-Aired-in-Calendar-Year-1998-Winner_2.pdf|title=20th Annual News Documentary Emmy Awards For Programming Originally Aired in Calendar Year 1998 -Winners|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=June 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0168298/awards|title=Leslie Cockburn|website=IMDb|access-date=June 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n{{Main|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Virginia#District 5}}\nCockburn was the 2018 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[Virginia's 5th congressional district]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]]. Cockburn announced her candidacy in July 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rappnews.com/2017/07/15/rappahannock-resident-leslie-cockburn-launches-bid-for-u-s-congress-seat/|title=Rappahannock resident Leslie Cockburn launches bid for U.S...|first=John|last=McCaslin|date=July 15, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref> and secured a large majority of delegates over several rival candidates for the party's nomination in May 2018 at the district Democratic convention to succeed the outgoing Republican representative [[Tom Garrett (Virginia politician)|Tom Garrett]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roanoke.com/news/politics/cockburn-receives-th-district-democratic-nomination/article_f5e08b44-9431-5303-8224-4dc49dc02910.html|title=Cockburn receives 5th District Democratic nomination|date=May 5, 2018|last=Hammel|first=Tyler|publisher=The Daily Progress via roanoke.com}}</ref>\n\nAfter winning her party's nomination, she lost her election bid to her Republican opponent, [[Denver Riggleman]], in the 2018 general election; Riggleman garnered 165,339 votes (53.2%) compared to Cockburn's 145,040 votes (46.7%) and 547 votes (0.2%) were cast as [[write-ins]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://results.elections.virginia.gov/vaelections/2018%20November%20General/Site/Member%20House%20of%20Representatives%20(05).html |title=2018 November General |publisher=Results.elections.virginia.gov |date=1980-01-01 |accessdate=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCockburn lives in [[Rappahannock County, Virginia]], with her husband, [[Andrew Cockburn]], a journalist and film producer. They married in San Francisco in 1977 and have co-authored several books.<ref>Charles Mosley, editor, ''Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage, 107th edition, 3 volumes'' (Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.: Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd, 2003), volume 1, page 120</ref> They have three children together: Chloe Francis Cockburn (April 3, 1979), [[Olivia Wilde]] (March 10, 1984), and Charles Philip Cockburn (January 31, 1993).<ref>Charles Mosley, editor, ''Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage, 107th edition, 3 volumes'' (Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.: Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd, 2003), volume 1, page 120.</ref>\n\nCockburn had two brothers-in-law, the late [[Alexander Cockburn]] and [[Patrick Cockburn]], and the mystery writer [[Sarah Caudwell]] was her half-sister in law. Her former son-in-law was [[Tao Ruspoli]] and her current son-in-law is [[Jason Sudeikis]], and journalists [[Laura Flanders]] and [[Stephanie Flanders]] are her half-nieces by marriage, daughters of her half-brother in law [[Michael Flanders]]. Her parents-in-law were [[Claud Cockburn|Claud]] and Patricia Cockburn. She has four grandchildren.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Cockburn, Leslie (1998). ''Looking for Trouble: One Woman, Six Wars and a Revolution'',<ref name=\"Democracy Now!\">{{cite web | url=http://www.democracynow.org/1998/4/27/interview_with_leslie_cockburn | title=Interview with Leslie Cockburn | work=[[Democracy Now!]] | date=April 27, 1998 | accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref> [[Anchor Books]], {{ISBN|0-385-48355-4}}\n*Cockburn, Leslie (with Andrew Cockburn) (1997). ''One Point Safe, the True Story of Russian Nuclear Security'', Doubleday, {{ISBN|0-385-48560-3}}\n*Cockburn, Leslie (with Andrew Cockburn) (1991). ''Dangerous Liaison: The Inside Story of the U.S.-Israeli Covert Relationship'', HarperCollins Publishers, {{ISBN|0-06-016444-1}}\n*Cockburn, Leslie (1987). ''Out of Control: The Story of the Reagan Administration's Secret War in Nicaragua, the Illegal Arms Pipeline, and the Contra Drug Connection''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20190204153723/https://www.lesliecockburnforcongress.com/ Leslie Cockburn for Congress] - campaign website\n*{{C-SPAN|Leslie Cockburn}}\n**[http://www.c-span.org/video/?290533-1/qa-leslie-andrew-cockburn C-SPAN ''Q&A'' interview with Andrew and Leslie Cockburn about ''American Casino'', January 3, 2010]\n*{{IMDb name|0168298}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cockburn, Leslie}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of SOAS University of London]]\n[[Category:American documentary filmmakers]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:American foreign policy writers]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American television news producers]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:American women war correspondents]]\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:Cockburn family|Leslie]]\n[[Category:People from Hillsborough, California]]\n[[Category:People from San Mateo, California]]\n[[Category:Princeton University faculty]]\n[[Category:Television producers from California]]\n[[Category:Women memoirists]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Virginia Democrats]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Women television producers]]\n[[Category:Women documentary filmmakers]]\n", "name_user": "Dawkeye", "label": "safe", "comment": "fmt/update references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leslie_Cockburn"}
{"title_page": "The Park Is Mine (1986 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Park Is Mine\n| image                = The Park Is Mine VideoCover.jpeg\n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = Drama<br />Thriller<br />Action\n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = [[Stephen Peters (writer)|Stephen Peters]] ([[The Park Is Mine (novel)|novel]])<br />[[Lyle Gorch]] (screenplay)\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[Steven Hilliard Stern]]\n| starring             = [[Tommy Lee Jones]]<br />[[Helen Shaver]]<br />\n[[Eric Peterson]]<br />\n[[Yaphet Kotto]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = [[Christopher Franke]]<br />[[Edgar Froese]]<br />[[Johannes Schmoelling]]<br />([[Tangerine Dream]])\n| country              = Canada\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = [[Denis H\u00e9roux]]<br />[[John Kemeny (producer)|John Kemeny]]\n| editor               = [[Ronald Sanders (film editor)|Ronald Sanders]]\n| cinematography       = [[Laszlo George]]\n| runtime              = 102 minutes\n| company              = [[International Cinema]]<br />[[Ramble Film Productions]]<br>[[HBO Pictures|HBO Premiere Films]]\n| distributor          = Astral Films<br>[[20th Television]]<br>[[Walt Disney Television]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = [[HBO]]\n| first_aired          = 6 October 1985 (USA)<br>3 January 1986 (Canada)\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''The Park Is Mine''''' is a Canadian-American drama [[television film]]  based on the novel of the same name by Stephen Peters. The film focuses on [[Vietnam War]] veteran, Mitch ([[Tommy Lee Jones]]), who takes forceful control of Central Park to remember those who served and died in the Vietnam War and draw attention to veterans' issues.<ref name= \"IMDB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0091724/?ref_=fn_al_tt_1/|title=IMDB|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Tommy Lee Jones]] as Mitch Garnett\n* [[Helen Shaver]] as Valery\n* [[Yaphet Kotto]] as Eubanks\n* [[Lawrence Dane]] as Commissioner Keller\n* [[Peter Dvorsky (actor)|Peter Dvorsky]] as Dix\n* [[Eric Peterson]] as Mike Johnson\n* [[Gale Garnett]] as Rachel\n* [[Denis Simpson]] as Richie\n* [[Reg Dreger]] as Commander Curran\n* [[Louis Di Bianco]] as Captain Juliano\n* [[Carl Marotte]] as Santini\n* [[Dennis O'Connor (actor)]] as Sergeant Duffy\n* [[Tom Harvey (actor)|Tom Harvey]] as General Bryant\n* [[R. D. Reid]] as Policeman on Ledge\n* [[George Bloomfield]] as Dr. Mueller\n* [[Marvin Karon]] as Warburton\n* [[Jong Soo Park]] as Tran Chan Dinh\n* [[Peter Langley]] as Verdanken\n* [[Robert Windsor]] as Minister\n* [[Stewart Arnott]] as Newsman \u2013 V.A. Hospital\n* [[Jennifer Dean]] as Detective Balkan\n* [[Andrew Thomson (actor)|Andrew Thomson]] as Transmission Officer\n* [[Allan Aarons]] as Policeman \u2013 V.A. Hospital\n* [[James Kidnie]] as Policeman in Park\n* Michael Copeman as Man at Desk\n* [[Philip Akin]] as Hardy\n* [[Ardon Bess]] as Daniels\n* [[Gregory Francis Kruger]] as T-shirt haggler\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released in 1985 on VHS by Key Video. It had originally been released on DVD overseas, but not in the United States, save for bootlegs. However, on December 13, 2016, Kino Lorber released the first official Blu-ray Disc and DVD.<ref name= \"The Park is Mine\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Park-Mine-Blu-ray-Tommy-Jones/dp/B01LWPK5HT/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1485625247&sr=8-1&keywords=the+park+is+mine/|title=The Park is Mine on sale at Amazon|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Park Is Mine\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Tangerine Dream]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 1991\n| recorded   = 1985\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Electronic music]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Silva Screen\n| producer   = Tangerine Dream\n| prev_title = [[Dead Solid Perfect#Soundtrack|Dead Solid Perfect]]\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[The Man Inside (1990 film)#Soundtrack|L'Affaire Wallraff (The Man Inside)]]\n| next_year  = 1991\n}}\n\n'''''The Park Is Mine''''' is the sixteenth soundtrack album released by [[Tangerine Dream]] and their forty-second released album overall. It was recorded in 1985 but not released until 1991. All tracks were composed by Edgar Froese, Christoph Franke, and Johannes Schmoelling.<ref>{{discogs release|179919|The Park Is Mine}}</ref><ref>{{cite vitn |title=Dead Solid Perfect |utl=the_park_is_mine}}</ref>\n\n{{track listing\n|title1=The Park Is Mine (Main Title) |length1=1:16\n|title2=Fatal Fall/Funeral |length2=2:16\n|title3=The Letter (Parts 1 & 2) |length3=5:18\n|title4=Taking the Park (Parts 1 & 2) |length4=8:28\n|title5=Swatting S.W.A.T. |length5=7:23\n|title6=Love Theme |length6=3:32\n|title7=The Helicopter Attack |length7=4:40\n|title8=Morning |length8=1:20\n|title9=We're Running Out of Time |length9=1:01\n|title10=The Claymore Mine/Stalking |length10=5:22\n|title11=The Final Confrontation/The Park is Yours! |length11=3:34\n|title12=Finale/End Credits |length12=6:19\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0091724|title=The Park Is Mine}}\n\n{{Tangerine Dream}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Park Is Mine}}\n[[Category:1986 films]]\n[[Category:1980s action films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Canadian television films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Steven Hilliard Stern]]\n[[Category:Central Park|Park Is Mine 1986]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by John Kemeny]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Tangerine Dream]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Park Is Mine\n| image                = The Park Is Mine VideoCover.jpeg\n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = Drama<br />Thriller<br />Action\n| creator              = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = [[Stephen Peters (writer)|Stephen Peters]] ([[The Park Is Mine (novel)|novel]])<br />[[Lyle Gorch]] (screenplay)\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[Steven Hilliard Stern]]\n| starring             = [[Tommy Lee Jones]]<br />[[Helen Shaver]]<br />\n[[Eric Peterson]]<br />\n[[Yaphet Kotto]]\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = [[Christopher Franke]]<br />[[Edgar Froese]]<br />[[Johannes Schmoelling]]<br />([[Tangerine Dream]])\n| country              = Canada\n| language             = English\n| num_episodes         = \n| producer             = [[Denis H\u00e9roux]]<br />[[John Kemeny (producer)|John Kemeny]]\n| editor               = [[Ronald Sanders (film editor)|Ronald Sanders]]\n| cinematography       = [[Laszlo George]]\n| runtime              = 102 minutes\n| company              = [[International Cinema]]<br />[[Ramble Film Productions]]<br>[[HBO Pictures|HBO Premiere Films]]\n| distributor          = Astral Films<br>[[20th Television]]<br>[[Walt Disney Television]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = [[HBO]]\n| first_aired          = 6 October 1985 (USA)<br>3 January 1986 (Canada)\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n'''''The Park Is Mine''''' is a Canadian-American drama [[television film]]  based on the novel of the same name by Stephen Peters. The film focuses on [[Vietnam War]] veteran, Mitch ([[Tommy Lee Jones]]), who takes forceful control of Central Park to remember those who served and died in the Vietnam War and draw attention to veterans' issues.<ref name= \"IMDB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0091724/?ref_=fn_al_tt_1/|title=IMDB|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Tommy Lee Jones]] as Mitch\n* [[Helen Shaver]] as Valery\n* [[Yaphet Kotto]] as Eubanks\n* [[Lawrence Dane]] as Commissioner Keller\n* [[Peter Dvorsky (actor)|Peter Dvorsky]] as Dix\n* [[Eric Peterson]] as Mike\n* [[Gale Garnett]] as Rachel\n* [[Denis Simpson]] as Richie\n* [[Reg Dreger]] as Commander Curran\n* [[Louis Di Bianco]] as Captain Juliano\n* [[Carl Marotte]] as Santini\n* [[Dennis O'Connor (actor)]] as Sergeant Duffy\n* [[Tom Harvey (actor)|Tom Harvey]] as General Bryant\n* [[R. D. Reid]] as Policeman on Ledge\n* [[George Bloomfield]] as Dr. Mueller\n* [[Marvin Karon]] as Warburton\n* [[Jong Soo Park]] as Tran Chan Dinh\n* [[Peter Langley]] as Verdanken\n* [[Robert Windsor]] as Minister\n* [[Stewart Arnott]] as Newsman \u2013 V.A. Hospital\n* [[Jennifer Dean]] as Detective Balkan\n* [[Andrew Thomson (actor)|Andrew Thomson]] as Transmission Officer\n* [[Allan Aarons]] as Policeman \u2013 V.A. Hospital\n* [[James Kidnie]] as Policeman in Park\n* Michael Copeman as Man at Desk\n* [[Philip Akin]] as Hardy\n* [[Ardon Bess]] as Daniels\n* [[Gregory Francis Kruger]] as T-shirt haggler\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released in 1985 on VHS by Key Video. It had originally been released on DVD overseas, but not in the United States, save for bootlegs. However, on December 13, 2016, Kino Lorber released the first official Blu-ray Disc and DVD.<ref name= \"The Park is Mine\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Park-Mine-Blu-ray-Tommy-Jones/dp/B01LWPK5HT/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1485625247&sr=8-1&keywords=the+park+is+mine/|title=The Park is Mine on sale at Amazon|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Park Is Mine\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Tangerine Dream]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 1991\n| recorded   = 1985\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Electronic music]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Silva Screen\n| producer   = Tangerine Dream\n| prev_title = [[Dead Solid Perfect#Soundtrack|Dead Solid Perfect]]\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[The Man Inside (1990 film)#Soundtrack|L'Affaire Wallraff (The Man Inside)]]\n| next_year  = 1991\n}}\n\n'''''The Park Is Mine''''' is the sixteenth soundtrack album released by [[Tangerine Dream]] and their forty-second released album overall. It was recorded in 1985 but not released until 1991. All tracks were composed by Edgar Froese, Christoph Franke, and Johannes Schmoelling.<ref>{{discogs release|179919|The Park Is Mine}}</ref><ref>{{cite vitn |title=Dead Solid Perfect |utl=the_park_is_mine}}</ref>\n\n{{track listing\n|title1=The Park Is Mine (Main Title) |length1=1:16\n|title2=Fatal Fall/Funeral |length2=2:16\n|title3=The Letter (Parts 1 & 2) |length3=5:18\n|title4=Taking the Park (Parts 1 & 2) |length4=8:28\n|title5=Swatting S.W.A.T. |length5=7:23\n|title6=Love Theme |length6=3:32\n|title7=The Helicopter Attack |length7=4:40\n|title8=Morning |length8=1:20\n|title9=We're Running Out of Time |length9=1:01\n|title10=The Claymore Mine/Stalking |length10=5:22\n|title11=The Final Confrontation/The Park is Yours! |length11=3:34\n|title12=Finale/End Credits |length12=6:19\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0091724|title=The Park Is Mine}}\n\n{{Tangerine Dream}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Park Is Mine}}\n[[Category:1986 films]]\n[[Category:1980s action films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Canadian television films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Steven Hilliard Stern]]\n[[Category:Central Park|Park Is Mine 1986]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by John Kemeny]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Tangerine Dream]]\n", "name_user": "Drewchas", "label": "safe", "comment": "The character Mike's last name is said at the 0:35 mark of the film, and the character Mitch's last name is said at the 3:19 mark of the film.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Park_Is_Mine_(1986_film)"}
{"title_page": "United Artists Records", "text_new": "{{short description|American record label}}\n{{Refimprove|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox record label <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Music -->\n| name        = United Artists Records\n| image       = United Artists Records vector.svg\n| parent      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[United Artists]] {{small|(1957\u20131978)}}\n* [[EMI]] {{small|(1978\u20131980)}}}}\n| founded     = {{start date and age|df=yes|1957}}\n| founder     = [[Max E. Youngstein]]\n| defunct     = {{end date|df=yes|1980|9}} (fate: absorbed into [[Liberty Records]] by [[EMI]])\n| distributor = Self-distributed\n| genre       = Various\n| country     = United States\n| location    = New York City, New York, U.S.<br>Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n}}\n\n'''United Artists Records''' was a record label founded by [[Max E. Youngstein]] of [[United Artists]]<ref name=\"Freudenheim\">{{cite web|last1=Freudenheim|first1=Milt|title=Max Youngstein, 84; Helped Run United Artists|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/11/business/max-youngstein-84-helped-run-united-artists.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=23 September 2017|date=11 July 1997}}</ref> in 1957 to issue movie soundtracks.<ref name=\"UA\">{{cite web|title=UA Sets Up Own Diskery Label|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UCkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20|magazine=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|date=14 October 1957 |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> The label expanded into other genres, such as easy listening, jazz, pop, and R&B.\n\n==History==\n===Genres===\nIn 1959, United Artists released ''Forest of the Amazons,'' a cantata by Brazilian composer [[Heitor Villa-Lobos]] adapted from the music he composed for [[MGM]]'s ''[[Green Mansions (film)|Green Mansions]]'', with the composer conducting the [[Symphony of the Air]]. Brazilian soprano [[Bidu Say\u00e3o]] was the featured soloist on the unusual recording, which was released on both LP and reel-to-reel tape.\n\nUnited Artists releases included soundtracks from the James Bond movies, ''[[It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World]]'' (1963), ''[[A Hard Day's Night (film)|A Hard Day's Night]]'' starring [[the Beatles]] (1964), ''[[The Greatest Story Ever Told]]'' (1965),  ''[[A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum (film)|A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum]]'' (1966), ''[[Fiddler on the Roof (film)|Fiddler on the Roof]]'' (1971), and ''[[Man of La Mancha (film)|Man of La Mancha]]'' (1972). The soundtrack album of United Artists's ''[[West Side Story (1961 film)|West Side Story]]'' (1961) was released by [[Columbia Records]], which had also released the Broadway cast album. Also, the American version of the soundtrack album of United Artists's ''[[Help! (film)|Help!]]'' (1965), also starring the Beatles, was released on [[Capitol Records]].\n\nAs [[Henry Mancini]] was signed to RCA Victor, that company handled the soundtracks of the United Artists films that he composed the music for, most notably ''[[The Pink Panther (film series)|The Pink Panther]]''; exceptions include ''[[Gaily, Gaily]]'', ''[[The Hawaiians (film)|The Hawaiians]]'', ''[[The Pink Panther Strikes Again]]'' and ''[[Revenge of the Pink Panther]]''. Many of these soundtracks have reverted to [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]], whose [[MGM Music]] unit licensed them to other labels for reissue, first [[Rykodisc]], then [[Universal Music]] and EMI. As owner of Columbia and RCA Victor, Sony released the ''West Side Story'' original cast album and film soundtrack on CD. Sony has owned most of Mancini's soundtrack albums since its music division's merger with [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]] in 2004.\n[[File:UnitedArtistsRecords.jpg|left|thumb|An earlier version of the United Artists Records logo used from 1960 through 1968]]\nThe label produced rock and roll and R&B hits from 1959 and into the 1960s by [[the Clovers]], [[Marv Johnson]], [[the Falcons]], [[the Exciters]], [[Patty Duke]], [[the Delicates]], [[Bobby Goldsboro]], [[Jay and the Americans]], and later [[Manfred Mann]] and [[the Easybeats]]. [[Berry Gordy]] placed a number of early [[Motown Records|Motown]] acts with United Artists, including Marv Johnson and [[Eddie Holland]] in 1959. [[Jerry Leiber]] and [[Mike Stoller]] were hired to produce artists signed to the label after they left Atlantic. These included the Exciters, [[Bobby Goldsboro]], [[Jay and the Americans]], the Clovers, and Mike Clifford. United Artists covered folk music when it added [[Gordon Lightfoot]] to its roster and easy listening with the addition of piano duo [[Ferrante & Teicher]].\n\nUnited Artists' involvement with jazz was significant. The company hired [[Alan Douglas (record producer)|Alan Douglas]] in 1960 to run its jazz division.<ref name=\"Pouncey\">{{cite magazine |last=Pouncey|first=Edwin |date=July 1997|title=The Man Who Sold the Underworld |magazine=The Wire|page=27 }}</ref>  Other producers were [[George Wein]], Jack Lewis, and [[Tom Wilson (record producer)|Tom Wilson]]. United Artist released jazz albums by [[Count Basie]],  [[Art Blakey]], [[Ruby Braff]], [[Betty Carter]], [[Teddy Charles]], [[Kenny Dorham]], [[Mose Allison]], [[Duke Ellington]], [[Art Farmer]], [[Bud Freeman]], [[Curtis Fuller]], [[Benny Golson]], [[Billie Holiday]], [[Milt Jackson]], [[Dave Lambert (American jazz vocalist)|Dave Lambert]], [[Booker Little]], [[Howard McGhee]], [[Gerry Mulligan]], [[Oliver Nelson]], [[Herb Pomeroy]], [[Bill Potts (musician)|Bill Potts]], [[Zoot Sims]], [[Rex Stewart]], [[Billy Strayhorn]], and the [[Modern Jazz Quartet]].<ref name=\"New Grove\">{{cite book|last1=Gardeber|first1=Mark|editor1-last=Kernfeld|editor1-first=Barry|title=The New Grove Dictionary of Jazz|date=2002|publisher=Grove's Dictionaries Inc.|location=New York|isbn=1-56159-284-6|page=172|volume=3|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, the [[Solid State Records (jazz label)|Solid State]] division was begun, recording several albums by [[The Thad Jones/Mel Lewis Orchestra]].<ref name=\"New Grove\" /> Other subsidiary labels were Unart, Ascot, United Artists Jazz, [[Musicor Records|Musicor]] (United Artists was half owner of the company from 1960\u20131964 before selling in 1965<ref name=\"Callahan\">{{cite web|last1=Callahan|first1=Mike|last2=Edwards|first2=Dave|last3=Eyries|first3=Patrice|title=The Musicor Records Story|url=http://www.bsnpubs.com/ua/musicorstory.html|website=www.bsnpubs.com|accessdate=23 September 2017|date=26 November 2006}}</ref> Ultra Audio (an audiophile label),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bsnpubs.com/ua/uaultraaudio.html |title=United Artists Album Discography (Ultra Audio Series) |publisher=Bsnpubs.com |date=27 October 2008 |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> and Veep. Unart was created in 1958 and was in operation until 1959, producing singles by vocal groups, then was recreated in 1967 for budget albums.\n\nIn 1966 United Artists acquired the masters of [[Sue Records]], an R&B and soul record label in New York City which produced [[Ike & Tina Turner]], [[Baby Washington]], and jazz organist [[Jimmy McGriff]]. Some material produced by Sue was reissued on Unart.\n\nUnited Artists produced a series of children's records under the \"[[Tale Spinners for Children]]\" name throughout the 1960s. These were album-length adaptations of classic fairy tales and children's stories done in an audio drama format.\n\n===Other UA labels===\n[[United Artists Special Projects]] were budget records designed for product and movie tie-ins. Examples are ''[[The Incredible World of James Bond#Record album|The Incredible World of James Bond]]'', an album sold by Pepsi Cola and Frito Lay of cover version themes and original soundtrack music of the first three James Bond films, and ''Music from Marlboro Country'', various cover versions of the theme to ''[[The Magnificent Seven]]'' and original soundtrack music from [[Elmer Bernstein]]'s ''[[Return of the Seven]]'' that was sold by [[Philip Morris USA|Philip Morris]] as a tie-in to its Marlboro cigarette brand.\n\n===Merger===\n[[File:UA liberty vector 1968.svg|right|thumb|United Artists Records used this logo from 1968 to 1971 when it was co-owned with Liberty Records.]]\nIn 1969, United Artists merged with co-owned [[Liberty Records]] and its subsidiary, [[Imperial Records]]. In 1971, Liberty/UA Records dropped the Liberty name in favor of United Artists.<ref name=\"absorbs\">{{cite web|title=UA Corp Absorbs Lines; UA Records Sole Disk Co.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ggEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA3|magazine=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=23 September 2017|date=23 January 1971}}</ref>\n\nMainstream pop acts were signed to the label, among them [[Traffic (band)|Traffic]], the [[Spencer Davis Group]], [[Peter Sarstedt]], [[Shirley Bassey]], and [[War (American band)|War]]. The label attempted to update the style of 1950s rock group [[Bill Haley & His Comets]] with a 1968 single. After UA bought [[Mediarts Records]], the roster grew to include [[Don McLean]], [[Merrilee Rush]], [[Paul Anka]], [[Chris Rea]], [[Dusty Springfield]], [[Bill Conti]], [[Northern Calloway]], [[Johnny Rivers]], [[Ike & Tina Turner]], [[Gerry Rafferty]], and [[Crystal Gayle]]. Later, through a distribution deal with [[Jet Records]], [[Electric Light Orchestra]] was signed. UA also distributed the otherwise-independent [[Grateful Dead Records]] in the early-to-mid 1970s.\n\nIn England, [[Andrew Lauder (music executive)|Andrew Lauder]], who had been head of A&R at the UK branch of Liberty Records, transferred to UA when Liberty was shut down in 1971. His signings included [[the Groundhogs]], [[Aynsley Dunbar]] (only in the UK), [[Hawkwind]], [[Bonzo Dog Band]], [[Brinsley Schwarz]], [[Man (band)|Man]] (all originally Liberty artists), [[High Tide (band)|High Tide]], [[Help Yourself (band)|Help Yourself]], [[Dr. Feelgood (band)|Dr. Feelgood]], [[the Buzzcocks]], [[the Stranglers]] and [[999 (band)|999]]. He also licensed UK releases for several influential German bands during the early 70s, the best known of which were [[Can (band)|Can]], [[Neu!]] and [[Amon D\u00fc\u00fcl II]]. Lauder left UA in late 1977 to help found [[Radar Records]].\n\nThe label's most successful artist was country artist [[Kenny Rogers]] who signed to UA in the mid-1970s, enjoying a long string of hit singles and albums.\n\nIn the mid-to-late 1970s the company was known as United Artists Music and Records Group (UAMARG).\n\n===Sale to EMI===\nIn 1978, UA executives Artie Mogull and Jerry Rubinstein bought the record company from Transamerica with a loan from [[EMI]], which took over distribution of the label. The official name of the company was changed to Liberty/United Records, but the United Artists Records name was retained under license. The deal led to an immediate setback, as the change of ownership allowed [[Jet Records]] to end its relationship with UA and switch its distribution to [[Sony Music Entertainment|CBS Records]], with the Jet back catalog transferring to CBS distribution as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LiUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT3|title=ELO 'Out Of Blue' Hassle Heating Up|magazine=Billboard|date=10 February 1979|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=16 September 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9CQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT101 |title=Jet In Global Pact |magazine=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |date=1 July 1978 |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> UA dumped many ELO albums into the [[Cut-out (recording industry)|cutout]] market, which CBS was unable to prevent.<ref name=\"cutout\">{{cite web|title=Cutout Material Is Plentiful at NARM|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LSQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT125|magazine=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=7 January 2012|language=en|date=7 April 1979}}</ref> However, CBS reissues of early ELO albums through ''[[Out of the Blue (Electric Light Orchestra album)|Out of the Blue]]'' (1977) contained copyright notices for United Artists Music and Records Group. Unable to generate enough income to cover the loan, Liberty/United Records was sold to EMI in 1979 for $3 million and assumed liabilities of $32 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LSUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PP1 |title=UA Acquisition Adds Clout for Cap-EMI |magazine=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |date=17 February 1979 |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nEMI dropped the United Artists name in 1980 and revived the Liberty label for releases by artists who had been signed to UA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_NyQEAAAAMBAJ |page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_NyQEAAAAMBAJ/page/n76 5] |title=Liberty 'New' Name Of UA |magazine=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |date=6 September 1980 |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> This incarnation of Liberty Records operated between 1980 and about 1986, when it was deactivated and its artists assigned to other EMI labels.\n\nMany albums from the United Artists Records catalog were reissued on Liberty during these years. Two significant exceptions were a couple of Beatles albums not previously controlled by EMI in the United States: the ''[[A Hard Day's Night (album)#North American release|A Hard Day's Night]]'' (1964) soundtrack album, and ''[[Let It Be (Beatles album)|Let It Be]]'' (1970). The ''Let It Be'' album was actually released by [[Apple Records]] in both the UK and the US but because the movie had been distributed by United Artists Pictures, in America the album was distributed by United Artists rather than EMI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dCkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8 |title=Beatlemania Returning As 'Let It Be' Clicking |magazine=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |date=6 June 1970 |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> Both previously non-EMI Beatles albums were reissued on the [[Capitol Records|Capitol]] label, which already controlled the rest of the Beatles' catalog in the United States.\n\n===UAR today===\nWhen producer [[Jerry Weintraub]] was enlisted to revive the [[United Artists]] movie studio in 1986, he attempted to revive the United Artists Records label as well. However, only one album was released: the soundtrack for ''[[The Karate Kid Part II]]'', a film Weintraub had produced for [[Columbia Pictures]] before being hired at UA. A single from the movie's soundtrack, Mancrab's \"Fish for Life,\" was also released on United Artists Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/ws46201us|title=Mancrab - Fish For Life|publisher=45cat|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe United Artists catalog is controlled by Capitol Records, now part of [[Universal Music Group]] (who also owns the non-soundtrack catalog of [[MGM Records]], once owned by UA's current parent [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BWUil8OuXS8C|title=The Music Business and Recording Industry: Delivering Music in the 21st Century|last=Hull|first=Geoffrey P.|last2=Hutchison|first2=Thomas William|last3=Strasser|first3=Richard|date=1 January 2011|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=9780415875608|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bsnpubs.com/mgm/mgmstory.html|title=The MGM Records Story|website=bsnpubs.com|access-date=25 March 2016}}</ref> Capitol Records also has the rights to soundtrack albums UA Records released under license from [[MGM Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000ICM5O4 |title=Rocky [Original Motion Picture Score&#93;: Bill Conti: Music |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref>  The catalog of British acts who were signed to the British branch of UA Records is today controlled by the [[Parlophone]] unit of [[Warner Music Group]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/warner-music-group-integrates-parlophone-667019 |title=Warner Music Group Integrates Parlophone Roster, Including Coldplay, David Guetta and Pink Floyd |website=The Hollywood Reporter |date=19 December 2013 |accessdate=9 July 2016}}</ref> with North American distribution by [[Rhino Entertainment]].\n\n==Roster==\n<!-- Please add names in alphabetical order -->\n{{div col|colwidth=27em}}\n* [[999 (band)|999]]\n* [[A Band Called O]]\n* [[Morris Albert]]\n* [[Amon D\u00fc\u00fcl II]]\n* [[The Animals]] (Jet)\n* [[The Angels (American group)|The Angels]] (Ascot)\n* [[Paul Anka]]\n* [[B. J. Arnau]]\n* [[Shirley Bassey]]\n* [[The Beatles]] (US and Canada)\n* [[Brass Construction]]\n* [[Brinsley Schwarz]]\n* [[Buzzcocks]]\n* [[Can (band)|Can]]\n* [[Al Caiola]] (Ultra Audio & United Artists)\n* [[Anita Carter]]\n* [[The Clovers]]\n* [[Odia Coates]]\n* [[Bill Conti]]\n* [[Pat Cooper]]\n* [[Cornelius Brothers & Sister Rose]]\n* [[Don Costa]]\n* [[Curfew (band)|Curfew]]\n* [[The_Fifth_Estate_(band)#Early_Years_(as_The_D-Men)|The D-Men]] (Veep & United Artists)\n* [[Chris Darrow]]\n* [[The Spencer Davis Group]] (US)\n* [[The Delicates]] (Unart)\n* [[Dr. Feelgood (band)|Dr. Feelgood]] (UK)\n* [[Patty Duke]]\n* [[The Easybeats]]\n* [[The Electric Indian]]\n* [[Electric Light Orchestra]] (United Artists & Jet)\n* [[Enchantment (band)|Enchantment]] (Roadshow Records and United Artists)\n* [[The Exciters]]\n* [[The Falcons]]\n* [[Ferrante & Teicher]] (Ultra Audio & United Artists)\n* [[Sergio Franchi]]\n* [[Connie Francis]]\n* [[Crystal Gayle]]\n* [[Bobby Goldsboro]]\n* [[The Groundhogs]]\n* [[Bill Haley & His Comets]]\n* [[The Hassles]]\n* [[Hawkwind]]\n* [[Roy_Head#Career|Roy Head & the Traits]] (Ascot)\n* [[Help Yourself (band)|Help Yourself]]\n* [[LeRoy Holmes]]\n* [[The Highwaymen (folk band)|The Highwaymen]]\n* [[Dee D. Jackson]]\n* [[Jan and Dean]]\n* [[Jay and the Americans]]\n* [[Marv Johnson]]\n* [[George Jones]]\n* [[Artie Kaplan]]\n* [[Deke_Leonard#Iceberg|Deke Leonard's Iceberg]]\n* [[Gordon Lightfoot]]\n* [[Little Anthony and the Imperials]] (DCP, Veep & UA)\n* [[Don McLean]]\n* [[Sylvia McNeill]]\n* [[Man (band)|Man]]\n* [[Manfred Mann]] (Ascot & United Artists)\n* [[Nathaniel Mayer]]\n* [[Bobbi Martin]]\n* [[George Martin]]\n* [[Garnet Mimms]]\n* [[Melba Montgomery]]\n* [[Mouth & MacNeal]]\n* [[The Move]]\n* [[Neu!]]\n* [[Maxine Nightingale]]\n* [[Nitty Gritty Dirt Band]] (Liberty & United Artists)\n* [[Passengers (Italian band)|Passengers]]\n* [[Joyce Paul]]\n* [[Gene Pitney]] (Musicor)\n* [[Popol Vuh (band)|Popol Vuh]] (rest of the world)\n* [[Mark Radice]]\n* [[Gerry Rafferty]]\n* [[Chris Rea]]\n* [[Sharon Redd]]\n* [[Del Reeves]]\n* [[Johnny Rivers]]\n* [[Tito Rodr\u00edguez]] (United Artists Latino)\n* [[Kenny Rogers]]\n* [[Jimmy Roselli]]\n* [[Merrilee Rush]]\n* [[Jean Shepard]]\n* [[Dusty Springfield]] (US)\n* [[The Stranglers]] (UK)\n* [[Donna Summer]]\n* [[The Tammys]]\n* [[Traffic (band)|Traffic]] (US)\n* [[Ike & Tina Turner]]\n* [[The Vapors]]\n* [[The Ventures]]\n* [[War (American band)|War]] (Far Out Productions)\n* [[Doc Watson]]\n* [[Wess|Wess and the Airedales]]\n* [[Dottie West]]\n* [[Whitesnake]]\n* [[David Wiffen]]\n* [[Bobby Womack]]\n* [[Roy Wood]]\n* [[Wynder K. Frog]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Liberty Records]]\n* [[Blue Note Records]]\n* [[Jet Records]]\n* [[List of record labels]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:United Artists Records| ]]\n[[Category:Jazz record labels]]\n[[Category:Pop record labels]]\n[[Category:Soundtrack record labels]]\n[[Category:Record labels based in California]]\n[[Category:Defunct record labels of the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:EMI]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 1957]]\n[[Category:Record labels disestablished in 1980]]\n[[Category:1957 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1980 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:United Artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American record label}}\n{{Refimprove|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox record label <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Music -->\n| name        = United Artists Records\n| image       = United Artists Records vector.svg\n| parent      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[United Artists]] {{small|(1957\u20131978)}}\n* [[EMI]] {{small|(1978\u20131980)}}}}\n| founded     = {{start date and age|df=yes|1957}}\n| founder     = [[Max E. Youngstein]]\n| defunct     = {{end date|df=yes|1980|9}} (fate: absorbed into [[Liberty Records]] by [[EMI]])\n| distributor = Self-distributed\n| genre       = Various\n| country     = United States\n| location    = New York City, New York, U.S.<br>Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n}}\n\n'''United Artists Records''' was a record label founded by [[Max E. Youngstein]] of [[United Artists]]<ref name=\"Freudenheim\">{{cite web|last1=Freudenheim|first1=Milt|title=Max Youngstein, 84; Helped Run United Artists|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/11/business/max-youngstein-84-helped-run-united-artists.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=23 September 2017|date=11 July 1997}}</ref> in 1957 to issue movie soundtracks.<ref name=\"UA\">{{cite web|title=UA Sets Up Own Diskery Label|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UCkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20|magazine=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|date=14 October 1957 |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> The label expanded into other genres, such as easy listening, jazz, pop, and R&B.\n\n==History==\n===Genres===\nIn 1959, United Artists released ''Forest of the Amazons,'' a cantata by Brazilian composer [[Heitor Villa-Lobos]] adapted from the music he composed for [[MGM]]'s ''[[Green Mansions (film)|Green Mansions]]'', with the composer conducting the [[Symphony of the Air]]. Brazilian soprano [[Bidu Say\u00e3o]] was the featured soloist on the unusual recording, which was released on both LP and reel-to-reel tape.\n\nUnited Artists releases included soundtracks from the James Bond movies, ''[[It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World]]'' (1963), ''[[A Hard Day's Night (film)|A Hard Day's Night]]'' starring [[the Beatles]] (1964), ''[[The Greatest Story Ever Told]]'' (1965),  ''[[A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum (film)|A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum]]'' (1966), ''[[Fiddler on the Roof (film)|Fiddler on the Roof]]'' (1971), and ''[[Man of La Mancha (film)|Man of La Mancha]]'' (1972). The soundtrack album of United Artists's ''[[West Side Story (1961 film)|West Side Story]]'' (1961) was released by [[Columbia Records]], which had also released the Broadway cast album. Also, the American version of the soundtrack album of United Artists's ''[[Help! (film)|Help!]]'' (1965), also starring the Beatles, was released on [[Capitol Records]].\n\nAs [[Henry Mancini]] was signed to RCA Victor, that company handled the soundtracks of the United Artists films that he composed the music for, most notably ''[[The Pink Panther (film series)|The Pink Panther]]''; exceptions include ''[[Gaily, Gaily]]'', ''[[The Hawaiians (film)|The Hawaiians]]'', ''[[The Pink Panther Strikes Again]]'' and ''[[Revenge of the Pink Panther]]''. Many of these soundtracks have reverted to [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]], whose [[MGM Music]] unit licensed them to other labels for reissue, first [[Rykodisc]], then [[Universal Music]] and EMI. As owner of Columbia and RCA Victor, Sony released the ''West Side Story'' original cast album and film soundtrack on CD. Sony has owned most of Mancini's soundtrack albums since its music division's merger with [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]] in 2004.\n[[File:UnitedArtistsRecords.jpg|left|thumb|An earlier version of the United Artists Records logo used from 1960 through 1968]]\nThe label produced rock and roll and R&B hits from 1959 and into the 1960s by [[the Clovers]], [[Marv Johnson]], [[the Falcons]], [[the Exciters]], [[Patty Duke]], [[the Delicates]], [[Bobby Goldsboro]], [[Jay and the Americans]], and later [[Manfred Mann]] and [[the Easybeats]]. [[Berry Gordy]] placed a number of early [[Motown Records|Motown]] acts with United Artists, including Marv Johnson and [[Eddie Holland]] in 1959. [[Jerry Leiber]] and [[Mike Stoller]] were hired to produce artists signed to the label after they left Atlantic. These included the Exciters, [[Bobby Goldsboro]], [[Jay and the Americans]], the Clovers, and Mike Clifford. United Artists covered folk music when it added [[Gordon Lightfoot]] to its roster and easy listening with the addition of piano duo [[Ferrante & Teicher]].\n\nUnited Artists involvement with jazz was significant. The company hired [[Alan Douglas (record producer)|Alan Douglas]] in 1960 to run its jazz division.<ref name=\"Pouncey\">{{cite web |last= Pouncey|first=Edwin |date=July 1997|title=The Man Who Sold the Underworld |magazine=The Wire|page=27 }}</ref>  Other producers were [[George Wein]], Jack Lewis, and [[Tom Wilson (record producer)|Tom Wilson]]. United Artist released jazz albums by [[Count Basie]],  [[Art Blakey]], [[Ruby Braff]], [[Betty Carter]], [[Teddy Charles]], [[Kenny Dorham]], [[Mose Allison]], [[Duke Ellington]], [[Art Farmer]], [[Bud Freeman]], [[Curtis Fuller]], [[Benny Golson]], [[Billie Holiday]], [[Milt Jackson]], [[Dave Lambert (American jazz vocalist)|Dave Lambert]], [[Booker Little]], [[Howard McGhee]], [[Gerry Mulligan]], [[Oliver Nelson]], [[Herb Pomeroy]], [[Bill Potts (musician)|Bill Potts]], [[Zoot Sims]], [[Rex Stewart]], [[Billy Strayhorn]], and the [[Modern Jazz Quartet]].<ref name=\"New Grove\">{{cite book|last1=Gardeber|first1=Mark|editor1-last=Kernfeld|editor1-first=Barry|title=The New Grove Dictionary of Jazz|date=2002|publisher=Grove's Dictionaries Inc.|location=New York|isbn=1-56159-284-6|page=172|volume=3|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, the [[Solid State Records (jazz label)|Solid State]] division was begun, recording several albums by [[The Thad Jones/Mel Lewis Orchestra]].<ref name=\"New Grove\" /> Other subsidiary labels were Unart, Ascot, United Artists Jazz, [[Musicor Records|Musicor]] (United Artists was half owner of the company from 1960\u20131964 before selling in 1965<ref name=\"Callahan\">{{cite web|last1=Callahan|first1=Mike|last2=Edwards|first2=Dave|last3=Eyries|first3=Patrice|title=The Musicor Records Story|url=http://www.bsnpubs.com/ua/musicorstory.html|website=www.bsnpubs.com|accessdate=23 September 2017|date=26 November 2006}}</ref> Ultra Audio (an audiophile label),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bsnpubs.com/ua/uaultraaudio.html |title=United Artists Album Discography (Ultra Audio Series) |publisher=Bsnpubs.com |date=27 October 2008 |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> and Veep. Unart was created in 1958 and was in operation until 1959, producing singles by vocal groups, then was recreated in 1967 for budget albums.\n\nIn 1966 United Artists acquired the masters of [[Sue Records]], an R&B and soul record label in New York City which produced [[Ike & Tina Turner]], [[Baby Washington]], and jazz organist [[Jimmy McGriff]]. Some material produced by Sue was reissued on Unart.\n\nUnited Artists produced a series of children's records under the \"[[Tale Spinners for Children]]\" name throughout the 1960s. These were album-length adaptations of classic fairy tales and children's stories done in an audio drama format.\n\n===Other UA labels===\n[[United Artists Special Projects]] were budget records designed for product and movie tie-ins. Examples are ''[[The Incredible World of James Bond#Record album|The Incredible World of James Bond]]'', an album sold by Pepsi Cola and Frito Lay of cover version themes and original soundtrack music of the first three James Bond films, and ''Music from Marlboro Country'', various cover versions of the theme to ''[[The Magnificent Seven]]'' and original soundtrack music from [[Elmer Bernstein]]'s ''[[Return of the Seven]]'' that was sold by [[Philip Morris USA|Philip Morris]] as a tie-in to its Marlboro cigarette brand.\n\n===Merger===\n[[File:UA liberty vector 1968.svg|right|thumb|United Artists Records used this logo from 1968 to 1971 when it was co-owned with Liberty Records.]]\nIn 1969, United Artists merged with co-owned [[Liberty Records]] and its subsidiary, [[Imperial Records]]. In 1971, Liberty/UA Records dropped the Liberty name in favor of United Artists.<ref name=\"absorbs\">{{cite web|title=UA Corp Absorbs Lines; UA Records Sole Disk Co.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ggEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA3|magazine=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=23 September 2017|date=23 January 1971}}</ref>\n\nMainstream pop acts were signed to the label, among them [[Traffic (band)|Traffic]], the [[Spencer Davis Group]], [[Peter Sarstedt]], [[Shirley Bassey]], and [[War (American band)|War]]. The label attempted to update the style of 1950s rock group [[Bill Haley & His Comets]] with a 1968 single. After UA bought [[Mediarts Records]], the roster grew to include [[Don McLean]], [[Merrilee Rush]], [[Paul Anka]], [[Chris Rea]], [[Dusty Springfield]], [[Bill Conti]], [[Northern Calloway]], [[Johnny Rivers]], [[Ike & Tina Turner]], [[Gerry Rafferty]], and [[Crystal Gayle]]. Later, through a distribution deal with [[Jet Records]], [[Electric Light Orchestra]] was signed. UA also distributed the otherwise-independent [[Grateful Dead Records]] in the early-to-mid 1970s.\n\nIn England, [[Andrew Lauder (music executive)|Andrew Lauder]], who had been head of A&R at the UK branch of Liberty Records, transferred to UA when Liberty was shut down in 1971. His signings included [[the Groundhogs]], [[Aynsley Dunbar]] (only in the UK), [[Hawkwind]], [[Bonzo Dog Band]], [[Brinsley Schwarz]], [[Man (band)|Man]] (all originally Liberty artists), [[High Tide (band)|High Tide]], [[Help Yourself (band)|Help Yourself]], [[Dr. Feelgood (band)|Dr. Feelgood]], [[the Buzzcocks]], [[the Stranglers]] and [[999 (band)|999]]. He also licensed UK releases for several influential German bands during the early 70s, the best known of which were [[Can (band)|Can]], [[Neu!]] and [[Amon D\u00fc\u00fcl II]]. Lauder left UA in late 1977 to help found [[Radar Records]].\n\nThe label's most successful artist was country artist [[Kenny Rogers]] who signed to UA in the mid-1970s, enjoying a long string of hit singles and albums.\n\nIn the mid-to-late 1970s the company was known as United Artists Music and Records Group (UAMARG).\n\n===Sale to EMI===\nIn 1978, UA executives Artie Mogull and Jerry Rubinstein bought the record company from Transamerica with a loan from [[EMI]], which took over distribution of the label. The official name of the company was changed to Liberty/United Records, but the United Artists Records name was retained under license. The deal led to an immediate setback, as the change of ownership allowed [[Jet Records]] to end its relationship with UA and switch its distribution to [[Sony Music Entertainment|CBS Records]], with the Jet back catalog transferring to CBS distribution as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LiUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT3|title=ELO 'Out Of Blue' Hassle Heating Up|magazine=Billboard|date=10 February 1979|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=16 September 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9CQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT101 |title=Jet In Global Pact |magazine=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |date=1 July 1978 |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> UA dumped many ELO albums into the [[Cut-out (recording industry)|cutout]] market, which CBS was unable to prevent.<ref name=\"cutout\">{{cite web|title=Cutout Material Is Plentiful at NARM|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LSQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT125|magazine=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=7 January 2012|language=en|date=7 April 1979}}</ref> However, CBS reissues of early ELO albums through ''[[Out of the Blue (Electric Light Orchestra album)|Out of the Blue]]'' (1977) contained copyright notices for United Artists Music and Records Group. Unable to generate enough income to cover the loan, Liberty/United Records was sold to EMI in 1979 for $3 million and assumed liabilities of $32 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LSUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PP1 |title=UA Acquisition Adds Clout for Cap-EMI |magazine=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |date=17 February 1979 |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nEMI dropped the United Artists name in 1980 and revived the Liberty label for releases by artists who had been signed to UA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_NyQEAAAAMBAJ |page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_NyQEAAAAMBAJ/page/n76 5] |title=Liberty 'New' Name Of UA |magazine=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |date=6 September 1980 |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> This incarnation of Liberty Records operated between 1980 and about 1986, when it was deactivated and its artists assigned to other EMI labels.\n\nMany albums from the United Artists Records catalog were reissued on Liberty during these years. Two significant exceptions were a couple of Beatles albums not previously controlled by EMI in the United States: the ''[[A Hard Day's Night (album)#North American release|A Hard Day's Night]]'' (1964) soundtrack album, and ''[[Let It Be (Beatles album)|Let It Be]]'' (1970). The ''Let It Be'' album was actually released by [[Apple Records]] in both the UK and the US but because the movie had been distributed by United Artists Pictures, in America the album was distributed by United Artists rather than EMI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dCkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8 |title=Beatlemania Returning As 'Let It Be' Clicking |magazine=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |date=6 June 1970 |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref> Both previously non-EMI Beatles albums were reissued on the [[Capitol Records|Capitol]] label, which already controlled the rest of the Beatles' catalog in the United States.\n\n===UAR today===\nWhen producer [[Jerry Weintraub]] was enlisted to revive the [[United Artists]] movie studio in 1986, he attempted to revive the United Artists Records label as well. However, only one album was released: the soundtrack for ''[[The Karate Kid Part II]]'', a film Weintraub had produced for [[Columbia Pictures]] before being hired at UA. A single from the movie's soundtrack, Mancrab's \"Fish for Life,\" was also released on United Artists Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/ws46201us|title=Mancrab - Fish For Life|publisher=45cat|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe United Artists catalog is controlled by Capitol Records, now part of [[Universal Music Group]] (who also owns the non-soundtrack catalog of [[MGM Records]], once owned by UA's current parent [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BWUil8OuXS8C|title=The Music Business and Recording Industry: Delivering Music in the 21st Century|last=Hull|first=Geoffrey P.|last2=Hutchison|first2=Thomas William|last3=Strasser|first3=Richard|date=1 January 2011|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=9780415875608|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bsnpubs.com/mgm/mgmstory.html|title=The MGM Records Story|website=bsnpubs.com|access-date=25 March 2016}}</ref> Capitol Records also has the rights to soundtrack albums UA Records released under license from [[MGM Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000ICM5O4 |title=Rocky [Original Motion Picture Score&#93;: Bill Conti: Music |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref>  The catalog of British acts who were signed to the British branch of UA Records is today controlled by the [[Parlophone]] unit of [[Warner Music Group]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/warner-music-group-integrates-parlophone-667019 |title=Warner Music Group Integrates Parlophone Roster, Including Coldplay, David Guetta and Pink Floyd |publisher=The Hollywood Reporter |date=19 December 2013 |accessdate=9 July 2016}}</ref> with North American distribution by [[Rhino Entertainment]].\n\n==Roster==\n<!-- Please add names in alphabetical order -->\n{{div col|colwidth=27em}}\n* [[999 (band)|999]]\n* [[A Band Called O]]\n* [[Morris Albert]]\n* [[Amon D\u00fc\u00fcl II]]\n* 